Ad Text:
ASIS is Australia’s overseas secret intelligence collection agency. Its mission is to protect and promote Australia’s vital interests through the provision of intelligence services as directed by the Australian Government.

ASIS employs people in a wide range of roles, including technologists. These roles require dynamic team players who enjoy working with stakeholders, team members and individually on projects. ASIS is looking for people who will be able to meet tight deadlines and work to support ASIS priorities. Successful candidates will have excellent coordination and administration skills, excellent verbal and written communication skills; and, strong stakeholder engagement and influencing skills. Relevant tertiary qualifications and demonstrable experience will be highly regarded.

ASIS values workplace diversity and is committed to providing a supportive, inclusive and respectful work environment. We encourage applications from Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander People, women, people with disabilities, people that identify as LGBTIQ+ and people from culturally and linguistically diverse backgrounds. We offer a competitive salary packing, including 22 days annual leave, shutdown between Christmas and New Year’s Day, 15.4% employer superannuation contribution, access to flex time (up to Level 6 only) and generous paid maternity/paternity leave.

Positions for these roles are based in Canberra and/or Adelaide CBD. These roles require the successful applicants to obtain and maintain a security clearance.  

AI, Machine Learning, Data Science & Analytics (Level 4—EL1)

Are you keen to design and develop world-class capabilities, turning data into knowledge and operational outcomes? Are you passionate about building solutions to allow data to tell its story? ASIS offers an opportunity to achieve these goals in an uncompromisingly unique environment. As a Data Professional in ASIS, you will have the chance to actively enable our operational teams to make the best use of ASIS’s unique data assets. ASIS leverages the wide world of open-source software and supplements it with our own development to deliver the bespoke tools required for the ASIS mission. Among our core languages are Python, Scala, Java, C++, Rust and JavaScript. Our toolset includes Spring, PyTorch, Tensorflow, Apache Spark, Apache Accumulo, Apache Hadoop, Apache NiFi, Apache Solr, Ansible and Git. We leverage structured and unstructured data, including geospatial and multilingual data sets of varying quality. Ideal candidates will be extraordinarily innovative, self-motivated and keen to use these toolsets to craft new systems that are simply not found in any other organisation. If this sounds like an environment you could thrive in, then apply for one of these unique positions.

Application Levels

A Level 4 candidate would be expected to be new to the area and work under the guidance and supervision of a more senior officer.

A candidate at the Level 5 level would be expected to have one to two years real-world experience and will be working under some supervision.

A Level 6 level candidate would be expected to have more experience and operate with limited supervision within a core group of developers.

A candidate at the EL1 level is expected to have substantial experience, and some deep technical expertise. They operate entirely independently and have the capacity to fulfil leadership roles as required.

Specialisations

We have a number of positions available including:

 Data Scientists at Level 4 to EL1; and

 MLOps Engineers at Level 5 to EL1

 Machine Learning Scientists at Level 4 to EL1; and

 Applied Mathematicians at Level 5 to EL1 

Please refer to the Selection Documentation for the job available through our Careers Page for more information.

Position Description and Selection Criteria: PD&PEWER_SM1_Senior Data Policy Advisor.pdf
 
Located in the ANU ARDC Canberra office
 
We offer a rewarding and challenging role
Help bring about a coherent policy environment supportive of better research through improved data usage
Help align and communicate how national infrastructure contributes to policy pillars of the Australian research system
Accommodating working arrangements

Position overview

The Australian Research Data Commons (ARDC) is Australia’s peak infrastructure for research data. Funded by the Australian Commonwealth Government through the National Collaborative Research Infrastructure Strategy (NCRIS). At the ARDC, we’re accelerating Australian research and innovation by driving excellence in the creation, analysis and retention of high-quality data assets. We partner with the research community, government and industry to build leading-edge digital research infrastructure.

The ARDC strategy puts the researcher at the center. Our purpose is to provide Australian researchers with competitive advantage through data. This is reflected in the matrix structure of the organisation, which groups staff into Business Units (Outreach, National Coordination, Services and Operations), and Strategic Pillars.

The ARDC is committed to diversity, equity and inclusion in the workplace. The ARDC seeks to foster an organisational culture that understands the value of individual differences and embraces and promotes treating all people with respect, dignity and equity. This is supported by the ARDC’s organisational values: Ambition, Focus, Collaboration, Flexibility, Transparency.

The Senior Data Policy Advisor in the Australian Research Data Commons will progress the ARDC mission through liaison with research organisations, peak bodies, funding agencies, and federal government bodies whose policies can affect the availability and re-use of research data.

Whilst neither a policy nor lobbyist organisation, the ARDC advocates for a coherent policy environment supportive of national research infrastructure. Equally the ARDC policy agenda seeks to both align and communicate how national infrastructure contributes to policy pillars of the research system, such as excellence, impact, integrity, innovation, and efficiency

The Senior Data Policy Advisor will work in close tandem with the ARDC CEO and in collaboration with staff throughout the ARDC. The Advisor will coordinate the work of the project officers, analysts and contractors within the context of specific projects

The successful candidate will

Take a lead role in developing and documenting the strategic research data policy agenda and managing its strategic implementation across ARDC
In conjunction with ARDC Senior Executive manage senior stakeholder liaison with research funders, sector peak bodies, and government departments and agencies.
Contribute strategic input into demonstrations of productivities, outcomes and impact of research enabled by national research data infrastructure.
Commission, write, or advise on position statements and submissions on matters of national Policy and national interest
Plan, design and assist with national symposiums and forums
Prepare communications materials, meeting documentation, web site materials, and reports
Oversee contracts with external experts for commissioned work

For further information please contact Dr Adrian Burton, ARDC Deputy CEO on E: adrian.burton@ardc.edu.au

The University actively encourages applications from Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people. For more information on employment opportunities, contact our Indigenous Employment Consultant on indigenous.employment@anu.edu.au 

ANU values diversity and inclusion and is committed to providing equal employment opportunities to those of all backgrounds and identities. For more information about staff equity at ANU, visit https://services.anu.edu.au/human-resources/respect-inclusion

FRV Australia, part of the global FRV Group, is a leading renewable energy developer and operator with a strong track record in solar and battery storage.

Since entering the market in 2011, the company has delivered landmark projects including Australia’s first large-scale solar farm and now manages over 1.4 GW of solar and storage assets in operation or development. With major projects such as the Gnarwarre 250 MW / 500 MWh battery and the Axedale hybrid solar and storage project, FRV combines global expertise with a local Sydney-based team to deliver innovative, sustainable energy solutions for the future.





THE ROLE




FRV Services Australia is looking for a Senior Business Intelligence Analyst / BI Lead to take ownership of performance analytics and business intelligence across our growing portfolio of renewable energy assets. This is a critical role ensuring continuity of asset performance reporting while also laying the foundations for a broader Business Intelligence function that will support Asset Management, Operations, Finance, and Compliance. 

The successful candidate will combine strong technical and analytical skills with the vision to build scalable BI capabilities. This role will serve as the anchor of FRV Australia’s future BI team, with scope to mentor junior analysts and shape the company’s approach to data-driven decision-making. 





MAIN RESPONSIBILITIES




Asset Performance & Continuity 

Monitor daily performance of FRV’s solar and BESS assets, alerting O&M contractors and Asset Managers of issues. 

Validate EPC/O&M contractor performance calculations against contractual guarantees. 

Calculate and analyse performance losses across the asset portfolio. 

Support Asset Managers with contractual, regulatory, and shareholder reporting requirements. 

Set up and maintain access to SCADA, EMMS/MSATS, dispatching, and operational platforms. 

Review and support PVsyst simulations, energy yield assessments, and digital twin development. 




Business Intelligence & Data Strategy 

Own the development of enterprise-wide BI dashboards and reports, starting with asset performance and expanding to finance, compliance, and operations. 

Build and maintain automated data pipelines (SQL, Databricks, cloud-based storage) to ensure reliable, high-quality reporting. 

Develop Power BI dashboards for executives and shareholders, integrating technical, market, and financial performance. 

Collaborate across teams to define KPIs and standardise metrics across the business. 

Identify and implement automation opportunities to reduce manual reporting. 




Leadership & Growth 

Act as the foundational member of FRV’s BI team, with scope to manage and mentor junior analysts. 

Partner closely with the Head of Asset Management to prioritise analytics needs and deliver actionable insights. 

Provide ad-hoc support across business functions, ensuring BI is embedded as a trusted partner in decision-making. 




EXPERTISE & QUALIFICATIONS




3–5 years’ analytics experience, ideally in renewable energy, utilities, or infrastructure

Degree in STEM, Data Analytics, or a related field

Skilled in SQL, Power BI, Databricks (or equivalent); Python and PVSyst desirable

Strong analytical skills with attention to detail and accuracy

Ability to turn complex data into clear, actionable insights for diverse stakeholders

Excellent communication, collaboration, and stakeholder management skills

Growth mindset, strong work ethic, and comfort working in fast-paced environments




OUR BENEFITS




Competitive salary.

22 days annual leave.

Employee Assistance Program (EAP).

Corporate membership and discount to ClassPass.

Birthday Leave.

Paid parental leave.

Training and development opportunities to enhance your career growth. 

Spanish Lessons. 

Collaborative and innovative culture. 

Corporate events and more!

All tools and PPE provided

At Alcoa, you will become an essential part of our purpose: to turn raw potential into real progress. The way we see it, every Alcoan is a work-shaper, team-shaper, idea-shaper, world-shaper.

About the Role

As the Regional Directional Studies Manager, you will play a pivotal role in shaping the future of our business. You will be responsible for identifying, evaluating, and developing strategic options for Alcoa's future growth, sustainability, and improvement initiatives. This position is central to shaping investment decisions and unlocking long-term value from our resources.

In this role, you will lead and coordinate strategic studies related to regional business options, geological exploration, and mine development planning. You'll lead cross-functional study teams, including consultants and contractors, and manage studies from early-phase concepts to pre-feasibility. You will need to use a strong balance of technical acumen, commercial insight, and stakeholder engagement to navigate complex factors and ensure all viable options are assessed.

A key part of your role will be your ability to use conceptual thinking and an analytical mindset to clearly define complex problems and explore multiple solution pathways. You will be responsible for leading teams through ambiguity and competing priorities to ensure that study outcomes are robust and strategically sound.

Key Responsibilities include:

Lead the analysis of options to determine which studies to advance; while also leading the development of early-phase studies to ensure they align with objectives, timelines, and budgets.

Coordinate with various functions, including operations, geology, finance, and external partners, to align study milestones with broader business timelines.

Ensure regulatory compliance for all study options and integrate safety and risk management, from hazard identification to risk assessments, into the study design from the very beginning.

Lead cross-functional study teams, mentor junior staff, and develop tools to track study progress and budget adherence.

Leverage strong communication and interpersonal skills to engage with diverse groups and synthesize their input into clear, cohesive recommendations.

Focus on delivering actionable and realistic studies, ensuring that conceptual ideas can be practically implemented.

What’s on offer

The opportunity to play a pivotal role in Alcoa’s growth and sustainability strategy.

Work with diverse teams and stakeholders across continents.

Attractive remuneration and variable bonus plan.

Employee growth and development opportunities.

Vehicle allowance and Superannuation above guaranteed rate.

Connect and be part of a community that celebrates diversity through our employee inclusion groups.

What you can bring to the role

A Tertiary Degree (e.g., a BSc) in Engineering, Geology, Mining, or a related field. A postgraduate degree (e.g., MBA, PhD, or a relevant Masters) is highly regarded.

Proven experience in mining or study/project management, including the ability to manage both direct and indirect stakeholders.

Demonstrated expert understanding of mining processes and risk management within a study coupled with proven experience in options analysis and the development of business cases that integrate both technical and commercial insights.

Strong communication, leadership, and stakeholder engagement skills, which allow you to work effectively with diverse teams and present findings to senior leadership.

Previous experience delivering completed studies that inform the capital project pipeline.

Additional information

Interviews may progress prior to the closing date, although all applications will be considered.

You will only be contacted if you are shortlisted for an interview, this process can take up to four weeks from the closing date.

Job description:



At ENGIE, great adventures always start with a simple "hello" and the desire to take action for tomorrow. If, like us, you strongly believe the energy transition holds opportunities for you and for everyone, then look no further, you belong with us!
Our goal is to be the best energy transition utility, and we have an ambition to reach net zero emissions by 2045. In Australia, this includes flexible power generation, energy retail services for homes and businesses, advanced energy management solutions, and a growing portfolio of future-focused projects — from hydrogen and battery storage to wind and solar developments.

The Role
We're looking for a commercially minded and analytically driven Commercial/Pricing Analyst to join our team and help shape pricing strategies in the dynamic and fast-evolving energy market. This role is critical in driving revenue growth, enhancing competitiveness, and supporting strategic decisions through robust financial modelling and market insights.

You'll work closely with senior stakeholders across the business, contributing to the development of pricing frameworks, business cases, and commercial models that support both retail and wholesale energy offerings.

Key Responsibilities

Develop and maintain pricing models that reflect market conditions, cost structures, and regulatory frameworks
Analyse revenue, cost drivers, and margin performance to support commercial decision-making
Use market intelligence and data to inform pricing strategies and product development
Build financial models and business cases for new energy products, services, and customer segments
Collaborate with cross-functional teams including Finance, Sales, Product, and Regulatory
Recommend improvements to pricing tools, processes, and governance
Support the adoption of new analytical tools and techniques to improve forecasting and scenario analysis

About You

Qualifications & Education

Undergraduate degree in Finance, Commerce, Accounting, or Business (other quantitative disciplines considered with strong financial modelling experience)

Skills & Attributes

Advanced financial modelling and analysis skills, with strong proficiency in Excel
Experience with Power BI, SQL, or other data tools is desirable
Strong commercial acumen, with the ability to link pricing and financial outcomes to broader market dynamics and energy strategy
Comfortable working with cost stacks, margin drivers, and regulatory pricing frameworks
Detail-oriented and proactive, with a focus on accuracy, continuous improvement, and delivering results under tight deadlines
Clear communicator, able to explain financial outcomes and trade-offs to both technical and non-technical stakeholders

Lead Performance Reports 


Where you'll be working 

 The Bureau of Health Information (BHI) is a board-governed organisation that provides independent reports on the performance of the NSW public healthcare system. BHI’s primary purpose is to provide timely, accurate and comparable information on the performance of the NSW public healthcare system in ways that enhance the system’s accountability and informs efforts to improve healthcare. Our vision is that BHI is the trusted provider of healthcare performance information, that our information is used to inform decisions, and that this information supports continued improvement to patients’ experiences and outcomes of care in NSW.

BHI shares the CORE values of NSW Health - Collaboration, Openness, Respect and Empowerment, and nurtures a culture of teamwork, innovation and excellence. As such we value diversity and inclusion and encourage people from different backgrounds to apply including Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people, people from different cultural backgrounds and people with disabilities. Our current team comprises people of diverse career and education backgrounds such as researchers, biostatisticians and data analysts, graphic designers, communication and data visualisation, as well as corporate governance specialists. Our people come from the NSW public and private sectors and other Australian and international organisations and systems. We value transferable experience and initiative as we grow and develop as an inclusive organisation.

BHI is located at 1 Reserve Road in St Leonard’s with great transport links, and local cafes and restaurants. We offer flexible working and accrued days off, as well as encouraging professional development in areas of interest and skills development. We are a vibrant team of people invested in intelligent reporting and best practice leading to real impact for the health sector and promote supportive collegiate relationships. 


What you'll be doing – Lead Performance Reporting 

The Lead Performance Reporting plays a key role in planning, developing and directing analysis and reporting for BHI's health system performance reports. In collaboration with other staff and with advice from stakeholders the Lead manages and contributes to all phases of the report production lifecycle, for a specific topic area. While doing so, the Lead contributes to appropriate positioning of the Bureau as a respected and trusted provider of timely, accurate and comparable information on the performance of the NSW public health system.

Fostering Key Partnerships: Build strong collaborations across the university and empower areas to facilitate workforce planning strategies in alignment with University workforce strategies.

Advocating for an Evidence-Based Culture: Lead a high-performing team and promote a culture of innovation, learning, and data-driven decision-making across the University.

You are an experienced leader in workforce planning and analytics, with a passion for data and proven track record of delivering strategic insights and driving organisational success in complex environments.

Excel in stakeholder engagement and collaboration across diverse organisational functions with experience with change management desirable.

Be an excellent listener and communicator, able to give voice to others while clearly conveying complex information to diverse audiences.

Possess the ability to lead high-performing teams and manage cross-functional initiatives with measurable impact.

Through its focus on fair remuneration, workforce insights, and policy guidance, ECD fosters a culture of compliance and continuous improvement, enabling the University to meet its obligations while attracting and retaining top talent.
